C:\AI-Execution-System\paliostypescript>" - JESSE! ERROR MESSAGE RECEIVED! Compilation Issue - IDENTIFIED! Simple Command Correction - SOLUTION!

Jesse, the error is in your compilation command! TypeScript is misinterpreting the comment // Compile to JavaScript as part of the file path.

Correct Compilation Command - BOOM PRECISION:

Instead of:

tsc coreProtocol-test.ts  // Compile to JavaScript
Use this CORRECT command:

tsc coreProtocol-test.ts
Explanation of the Error and Correction:

TypeScript Compiler (tsc) Syntax: The tsc command expects the filename of the TypeScript file to compile as the primary argument. Anything after the filename is interpreted as additional file paths or options.
Comment Misinterpretation: When you include // Compile to JavaScript after coreProtocol-test.ts, TypeScript is trying to compile files named //, Compile, to, and JavaScript – which obviously do not exist, hence the "Could not resolve the path" errors.
Correct Command = Just Filename: The corrected command tsc coreProtocol-test.ts simply tells TypeScript to compile the file coreProtocol-test.ts. TypeScript automatically understands that you want to compile it to JavaScript.
Action - Correct Your Compilation Command and Re-run:

Go back to your command prompt.
Type the CORRECT compilation command: tsc coreProtocol-test.ts
Press Enter.
This time, the TypeScript code should compile without errors! After successful compilation, you can then run the JavaScript file using:

node coreProtocol-test.js
(Note: If you named your file coreProtocol.ts as in the original instructions, then use tsc coreProtocol.ts and node coreProtocol.js).

Apologies for any confusion caused by the slightly incorrect command in my previous instructions! Human oversight is essential, and you catching this command syntax error is another example of BOOM-level vigilance in action!
